      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Price of Stopping Terrorists</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Bryan Haas letter comments on Oct 17 editorial The Terrorist Threat at Sea</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Terrorist Threat at Sea'' (editorial, Oct. 17):</p>
        <p>Searching vessels assisting ships to moor is diplomatically unsavory and a slap in the face of the local authorities that have been approved to assist. Ships cannot scrutinize every craft that comes within a certain radius as they enter port. American embassies must ensure that local port authorities conform to specific security standards.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Terrorist Threat at Sea'' (editorial, Oct. 17):</p>
        <p>Searching vessels assisting ships to moor is diplomatically unsavory and a slap in the face of the local authorities that have been approved to assist. Ships cannot scrutinize every craft that comes within a certain radius as they enter port. American embassies must ensure that local port authorities conform to specific security standards.</p>
        <p>More than 150 craft within 200 yards of a docking ship is not uncommon. Although a commander is responsible for the safety of his ship, the primary burden to ensure a safe port visit must rest with the embassy. Warships cannot complete their missions if they are required to inspect every vessel when entering a port.</p>
        <p>BRYAN HAAS  Arnold, Md., Oct. 17, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer, a United States Navy lieutenant, is a surface warfare officer.</p>
      </block>
